A gentle practice to soothe overwhelm and drop into your body. Touch is a fundamental human need and by placing our hands on our bodies, we can begin to experience this essential need with safety and tenderness. 

Self-touch can be a powerful way to anchor our nervous systems. Placing a hand at our brain stem offers contact and support that is calming, helping our bodies come into presence. A hand at the forehead offers an opportunity to contain fast or ruminating thoughts, giving the space to further root into our bodies. A hand on the heart is a tried and true practice for touching into our emotional body, acknowledging the ways that we leave or override our bodies while offering attunement to what is coming up in the moment.

These hand positions paired with gentle, slow breathing provide a well rounded regulation practice than can help in times of overwhelm or anxiety as well as moments when we long to reconnect with our bodies. You can also practice this before bedtime or in any moment when you want to give yourself slow care.

I hope this practice supports you. Please let me know how it goes in the comments. What did you feel? What did you notice? I would love to know. x

A few highlights from our little homestead. I want to remember how much we grew this year within  ourselves and with this land we are stewarding. Our family expanded in so many ways this year and experienced so many firsts. In the spring our beloved Little Sweetie gave birth to 6 healthy kittens in our home. We welcomed two rescue pups, four more kittens, and four mini donkeys - one who came to us pregnant. Yes, we will tending to a baby mini donkey this coming spring! When Nic told me news a few weeks ago I cried. It feels like such a blessing for our family, for this land.

We also cared for our garden and planted too many low water, native plants to count. Well over sixty including a few trees. We are now in the process of looking into a grey water and rain/snow catchment system for 2023 continuing to work with the land and with the rapidly changing environment. 

This year Sol turned four and Z had his first birthday. It’s looking like his adoption will happen in February which is huge. 

This year has not been without grief, tremendous challenges, and pain, however in this moment I want to remember how our family took care of each other as best we could, loved this land, and showed up fully, even when it hurt. Sending love from the Sierras. xo

Another trip around the sun! Yesterday was my new moon solar return. Thanks to @homesteadapothecary taking our two sick kiddos out into the sunshine, I had a few glorious hours of alone time in our home. It’s rare as a mom of young kids to even be able to take a quiet shower or bathroom break! The stillness in our home gave me the space to feel into this past year with some clarity and ability to allow all of my parts to have a seat at the table. 

This past year has been one for the books. It has been full of deeply uncomfortable and a times physically painful healing and expansion. It has been a year of unrelenting grief that I am starting to allow myself to explore. It has been a year of being slightly on edge waiting for the adoption to move forward. It has been a year of saying goodbye to relationships that don’t have space for the person I am evolving into.

This past year has also been sprinkled with moments of feeling what I am starting to recognize as joy. Moments of ease. Moments of rest. Moments of pausing. Moments of longer and slower exhales.

It is difficult to pinpoint just one thing that I have learned this year as I am in the midst of such profound, cellular level shifts and reorganization in my system. In certain moments I can feel a deep settling of the grief like it’s composting, like I am actually not at the beginning of this grief work but I am at the end of some major intergenerational pain cycles. The grief, the way it shapes and organizes my system when I feel it in connection with others is on the other side of what I’ve been longing for. On the other side of what I am calling in for myself during this next solar return. More connection. More vulnerability. More receiving. More of my blueprint. x

PS this is a video I took of myself last summer at the river with Nic and the kids. I wanted to remember how easy it felt, how connected we were, how much fun we had.

Today I shared a raw glimpse of my life as a foster mom in my Sunday newsletter. You’re welcome to read it on Substack through the link in my profile.

“The first twenty-four hours she was here I did not hold her. I would not let myself. I did not want to face the anticipated pain of her eventual departure. I watched Solomon and Zen talk to her and gently stroke her head. I watched Nic feed and change her and cuddle her to sleep. I kept my distance staying busy with our kids, house chores, animals, and work. At the end of day two Nic asked me to hold her while he went to the bathroom. The kids were asleep. The house was quiet. I held her six-pound body in my arms on our couch. My whole body exhaled. Tears streamed down my cheeks as I stared at her small face. Her breath was quiet. My heart was opening. And there wasn’t any closing it.”

With so much love, Ashley

Creating a container for grief. A few threads from my newest essay on Substack. To read the full letter visit the link in my bio. Back in my early days of sobriety I worked to keep grief at bay. I did everything I could to not feel sadness, rage, or any other unpleasant emotion because they were too much for my nervous system to handle. Any time I had big uncomfortable feelings I was triggered to get high, to get out of my body as quickly as possible. Today, the more willing I am to tend to myself while I am grieving, the more I will touch into my aliveness in the present moment. And I want to feel alive. And that aliveness includes the grief. With love, Ashley

PS This is a photo I took last week with mulberry stained fingers from our homegrown tree and the last photos is one of my favorite flowers, the matilija poppy, we grew those too. x

My latest Sunday letter. In 2020 my family and I moved to the Sierras in central California. Up until this move, I did not believe that I could live outside of a metropolitan area for more than a few months. My nervous system was entrained to the rhythm of survival. Transitioning to a slower pace was terrifying to the parts of me that were bound up with the rushed tempo of city dwelling and accustomed to suppressing other parts of me that were desperate for another way to inhabit my body and my life. Read the full letter on my Substack, link in bio. x

In today's letter I share what has been showing up for me with our new emergency foster placement. I haven’t done a great job these last few days. I am struggling, especially with the older boy’s behaviors. I know his behaviors are strategies for his suffering and are not his fault, but they are still very triggering to me.

Flash forward to right now, here is this young child showing me some of my deepest wounding all of these years later. He is mirroring back my own insecurities, emotional neglect, lack of attunement and connection from childhood. It is painful to revisit and see my younger parts in him. And even though I am showing up for my younger self and practicing breathwork and grief work it is still a lot. My capacity is not where I want it to be. My patience is thin. My anger isn’t fully integrated. I haven’t been able to access as much of my adult self as I would have liked to in these last days. 

Read the full letter over on Substack, link is in my bio. x

PS this is little me. x

A sense of urgency has permeated my life since childhood. It shows up as a pressing need to figure things out as quickly as possible, shallow or rapid breathing, feelings of never being enough, a sense of needing to get out of my body or a situation as fast as possible, and anxiety about the future.

Learning to rest has brought me in close contact with all the ways urgency shows up in my body and actions. It has shown me why I have spent years trying to outrun pain, grief, unworthiness, and connection. 

By taking the time to practice resting I have gradually been able to shift my baseline from a sense of urgency to one of curiosity, openness, and compassion. While I am far from ‘healed’ in this area, I am learning one moment of rest at a time that I am worthy of rest. I am worthy of ease. 

All of this and more in my new book Permission to Rest. Available for pre-order now at the link in bio.

In the beginning of my rest practice it looked mostly like taking naps and trying to get more sleep at night. While those practices remain an important part of my life, they are often not realistic, especially with three kids under five at home, working, and tending to the land. There is so much that requires my attention during the day and finding pocket rest practices that I can do in a few seconds or minutes has helped me to access rest in moments when I really need it. Sometimes it really is as simple as offering myself patience and slowness, looking up at the sky, or connecting with a few gentle cycles of breathing. I offer this list to you as a pathway to rest. Choose what calls to you and leave what doesn’t. There are no rules here, just orient toward what is going to support you accessing micro moments of rest throughout the day. x

For more invitations to rest please pre-order my new book Permission to Rest at the link in my bio and feel free to tag a friend who could use a little restorative support. x

Today I have a pretty full schedule and I noticed myself speeding up to get ready to leave the house. This is an old pattern in my nervous system, to rush through transitions, to rush through my days, to feel like I need to go as fast as possible. When I caught myself speeding up I took a few moments to check in with myself. I asked myself what I needed. Within a couple of seconds I became aware of a younger part of myself who was in fear about the day. I took some time to comfort her and integrate that fear. Within minutes I felt more regulated, resourced, and rested. I also recognized that I had more energy to face the day despite being up most of the night with Zen and my back feeling stiff today.

This was such a beautiful moment of practice, of turning inward, and of claiming the slower pace that I desire to move in today. I  want to acknowledge that practice came easy because I was home alone, Nic had already taken the kids out for the day. In situations where I feel that urgency to rush and I am not alone, practice often looks like me checking in with myself and then tending to whatever part that shows up later in the day when I have the time. That works really well too because it gives my system just enough space to slow down. 

A big part of learning to rest has been tuning into what rest feels like in my body. This helps me orient toward rest in moments when I am rushing or have the impulse to go fast. This is one of the practices in my new book Permission to Rest which comes out in just a few weeks. If you haven't pre-ordered yet you can visit the link in my bio for places to do so. Lastly, I'd love to learn, what does rest feel like in your body? x

Today's letter is deeply personal and the theme is outgrowing relationships. I share about the grief from the aftermath of a relationship rupture with a close friend and the self-honoring work that has helped me heal and evolve. 

For so much of my life I would override my body’s signals that I was unsafe and push through because of a sense of obligation, guilt, or other messaging I received growing up about what it means to be in relationships and what it means to be “good”. In this chapter of my life I am no longer willing to stay in relationships where it is not safe to be my full self and where people lack the capacity for repair. This is such deep and uncomfortable work. In the same breath it has given me the strength to stay the course and be willing to continue growing, no matter who is willing to show up for it. 

Read the full letter on Subtack at The Deeper Call. Link in my bio. I look forward to hearing your thoughts. x

#grief #evolution #outgrowingpeople #openheart #internalfamilysystems #selfcare #honoryourself #relationships #writer #healing

A gentle reminder to soften your eyes. This has been one of my steady practices for the last few years to downshift and orient to the present moment. Years ago in a trauma training I learned about how much stress, tension, and shock we can hold in and around our eyes. When I am running on urgency or in front of a screen for too long my eyes get very tense. The simple practice of giving my eyes the space to relax my eyes even for just a few moments is nourishing and restorative. 

Learning to rest has been a process and I have yet to arrive. What I notice when I practice micro moments of rest through softening my eyes is that I am more available for life and for me, that is one of my deepest intentions. To be here. To be available.

Our new rescue familiar, Elsa. On August 7th, @lacyannephillips posted Elsa in her stories (see second video) and she was going to be euthanized in 24 hours. For the next day, she, @homesteadapothecary and I made calls and eventually got a rescue to pull her. I had such a strong feeling, a knowing that she was supposed to be living with us.

For the last two months I have been in contact with the rescue on her progress and after taking care of all of her medical needs, she was ready to be picked up (slide 3).

Elsa (seems like the name is here to stay!), has been adjusting very well and is so happy playing with the other dogs and the kids. She definitely needs some training but her overall temperament and energy are such a dreamy fit with our pack. I am so grateful she is here and look forward to sharing more here with you. Also, if you are looking to rescue, check Lacy’s stories on Tuesdays as she shares the familiars that connect with her. 💕
